and I think that's it
You're allergic to arcane languages and you work in health IT? I find this hilarious.
I have enough of them
I'm so glad I'm not the only one who doesn't get Git, and can live with the SVN imperfections well enough to not be interested too much in switching...
Have you ever heard me call you, or anyone, stupid? Git has a learning curve!

The thing about distributed systems like git is that they totally change the way you think, and the things you can do. It becomes easier to collaborate in a wide ecosystem, where there are different projects happening at once.

I found that the Pro GIT book was very helpful in learning some of the standard Git processes and paradigms. It is available for free download here: https://progit.org

I also agree with Josh that some change of thinking is necessary (and will admit to occassionally falling into my old, ingrained habits).

And the question is - is it reasonable to expect the 60+ FHIR committers (some of whom aren't terribly technical) to mount that learning curve and do we have the resources to assist and support them in doing so. Given that some relatively technical people are finding it a non-intuitive curve (not that they couldn't mount it with dedication), it seems a big ask to move - particularly when there is no pressing functionality that we're missing with SVN

Well, git and github make pull requests really simple.... so you don't really need 60 committers, you just need a few people who are authorized to pull in forks. It also makes it easier for people to make changes and have them reviewed by a wide audience before the pull request is merged... for example, if we did end up making a change to xml and JSON syntax.

That's exactly right. There's no way we'd want 60 people making changes to (and often breaking) the core repository if we had better tools in place. With git and GitHub, people could fix errors in text, typos, etc, much more easily than today, and these would be reviewed before incorporating the changes back into the main repository.

Two issues with that: 1. HL7 process doesn't really have room for "vetting" of changes made to artifacts - there's no notion of a Linus Torvald who can decide what to accept or reject; 2. The logical people who could do such vetting are already stretched thin and this would create another bottleneck.
I don't think they need to be content evaluators they need to be process facilitators.
Actually, it would make it easier, because rather than doing everything themselves, they can delegate substantial tasks to others and simply review and merge the change.
